

Being able to easily see what’s happening inside your 
containers is essential for debugging (and will be very 
useful later when we look at Skupper routers, collectors, etc.).

Why this matters:

    * kubectl logs lets you see stdout/stderr from containers.

    * kubectl exec lets you run commands inside a running container 
      (like bash, ps, curl, etc.).


Together they give you the two most common ways to inspect live 
workloads without needing to SSH into nodes.

